TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hybrid Entrepreneurship
AU  - Folta, Timothy B.
AU  - Delmar, Frédéric
AU  - Wennberg, Karl
Y1  - 2009/11/06
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2010/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1094
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1090.1094
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 253
EP  - 269
VL  - 56
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In contrast to previous efforts to model an individual's movement from wage work into entrepreneurship, we consider that individuals might transition incrementally by retaining their wage job while entering into self-employment. We show that these hybrid entrepreneurs represent a significant share of all entrepreneurial activity. Theoretical arguments are proposed to suggest why hybrid entrants are distinct from self-employment entrants, and why hybrid entry may facilitate subsequent entry into full self-employment. We demonstrate that there are significant theoretical and empirical consequences for this group and our understanding of self-employment entry and labor market dynamics. Using matched employee?employer data over eight years, we test the model on a population of Swedish wage earners in the knowledge-intensive sector.
AB  - In contrast to previous efforts to model an individual's movement from wage work into entrepreneurship, we consider that individuals might transition incrementally by retaining their wage job while entering into self-employment. We show that these hybrid entrepreneurs represent a significant share of all entrepreneurial activity. Theoretical arguments are proposed to suggest why hybrid entrants are distinct from self-employment entrants, and why hybrid entry may facilitate subsequent entry into full self-employment. We demonstrate that there are significant theoretical and empirical consequences for this group and our understanding of self-employment entry and labor market dynamics. Using matched employee?employer data over eight years, we test the model on a population of Swedish wage earners in the knowledge-intensive sector.
